{"title_page": "Stephenie Landry", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Stephenie, Landry\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Businesswoman|Online retail executive}}\n| title              = Vice President, Amazon Grocery\n| known_for          = Creating [[Prime Now]]\n}}\n\n'''Stephenie Landry''' is an American business executive and vice president of [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/amazon/for-amazon-exec-stephenie-landry-the-future-is-now/|title=For Amazon exec Stephenie Landry, the future is Now|date=2016-05-21|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> She is in charge of Amazon [[Prime Now]] and [[AmazonFresh]], and she previously led [[Amazon Restaurants]] before the service was discontinued in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2017/12/21/16806778/amazon-stephenie-landry-prime-now-amazon-fresh-restaurants-food-delivery|title=Amazon has combined the leadership of Prime Now and Amazon Fresh under one rising-star executive|last=Rey|first=Jason Del|date=2017-12-21|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> She led the creation and launch of many other Amazon initiatives, such as Amazon Student, Amazon Mom, and [[Prime Pantry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/women-in-biz-qa-stephenie-landry-worldwide-vp-amazon_b_587ded35e4b06992b1b60ab6|title=Women in Biz Q&A: Stephenie Landry, Worldwide VP, Amazon Prime Now|last=Dunn|first=Laura Emily|last2=Comms|first2=ContributorDigital|date=2017-01-17|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=Content|last4=traveller|first4=Social Media Practitioner {{!}} Political Style blogger {{!}} digital democracy advocate {{!}} world}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nLandry earned a Women's Studies degree from [[Wellesley College]] and attended business school at the [[University of Michigan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=66f7dfa0-7dfd-11ea-be67-abbc59617d88&url=L25ld3MvdmlkZW9zLzIwMTgtMDMtMDgvYW1hem9uLXMtc3RlcGhlbmllLWxhbmRyeS1vbi1yaXNpbmctZnJvbS1pbnRlcm4tdG8tcnVubmluZy1wcmltZS1ub3ctdmlkZW8tamVpc3J0MTY=|title=Amazon's Stephenie Landry on rising from intern to running Prime Now video|website=Bloomberg Technology|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nLandry first came to Amazon as an intern in 2003 while she was attending business school, and she became a full-time Amazon employee in 2004.<ref name=\":1\" /> She started in operations, including work on logistics, transportation, supply chain, customer service, and warehousing, and she went on to create products that heavily leveraged operations.<ref name=\":0\" /> Landry held a series of jobs of increasing responsibility and in 2013, she became a Technical Advisor to Jeff Wilke, who runs Amazon's worldwide consumer business and is considered one of Amazon\u2019s most powerful executives.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2014, Landry went on to write a detailed memo outlining the idea for Prime Now, and the service launched 111 days later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/greg-satell/the-secret-behind-amazons-uncanny-ability-to-out-innovate-just-about-every-other-company-on-planet.html|title=How Amazon Innovates|last=Satell|first=Greg|date=2018-09-23|website=Inc.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] named Landry to its \"Next List 2016,\" as one of \"25 Geniuses Who Are Creating the Future of Business.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Staff|first=WIRED|url=https://www.wired.com/2016/04/wired-nextlist-2016/|title=25 Geniuses Who Are Creating the Future of Business|date=2016-04-26|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-14|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Landry, Stephenie}}\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American online retailer founders]]\n[[Category:American women business executives]]\n[[Category:Amazon.com people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wellesley College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Userspace draft|source=ArticleWizard|date=April 2020}} \n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Stephenie, Landry\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Businesswoman|Online retail executive}}\n| title              = Vice President, Amazon Grocery\n| known_for          = Creating [[Prime Now]]\n}}\n\n'''Stephenie Landry''' is an American business executive and vice president of [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/amazon/for-amazon-exec-stephenie-landry-the-future-is-now/|title=For Amazon exec Stephenie Landry, the future is Now|date=2016-05-21|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> She is in charge of Amazon [[Prime Now]] and [[AmazonFresh]], and she previously led [[Amazon Restaurants]] before the service was discontinued in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2017/12/21/16806778/amazon-stephenie-landry-prime-now-amazon-fresh-restaurants-food-delivery|title=Amazon has combined the leadership of Prime Now and Amazon Fresh under one rising-star executive|last=Rey|first=Jason Del|date=2017-12-21|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> She led the creation and launch of many other Amazon initiatives, such as Amazon Student, Amazon Mom, and [[Prime Pantry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/women-in-biz-qa-stephenie-landry-worldwide-vp-amazon_b_587ded35e4b06992b1b60ab6|title=Women in Biz Q&A: Stephenie Landry, Worldwide VP, Amazon Prime Now|last=Dunn|first=Laura Emily|last2=Comms|first2=ContributorDigital|date=2017-01-17|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=Content|last4=traveller|first4=Social Media Practitioner {{!}} Political Style blogger {{!}} digital democracy advocate {{!}} world}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nLandry earned a Women's Studies degree from [[Wellesley College]] and attended business school at the [[University of Michigan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=66f7dfa0-7dfd-11ea-be67-abbc59617d88&url=L25ld3MvdmlkZW9zLzIwMTgtMDMtMDgvYW1hem9uLXMtc3RlcGhlbmllLWxhbmRyeS1vbi1yaXNpbmctZnJvbS1pbnRlcm4tdG8tcnVubmluZy1wcmltZS1ub3ctdmlkZW8tamVpc3J0MTY=|title=Amazon's Stephenie Landry on rising from intern to running Prime Now video|website=Bloomberg Technology|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nLandry first came to Amazon as an intern in 2003 while she was attending business school, and she became a full-time Amazon employee in 2004.<ref name=\":1\" /> She started in operations, including work on logistics, transportation, supply chain, customer service, and warehousing, and she went on to create products that heavily leveraged operations.<ref name=\":0\" /> Landry held a series of jobs of increasing responsibility and in 2013, she became a Technical Advisor to Jeff Wilke, who runs Amazon's worldwide consumer business and is considered one of Amazon\u2019s most powerful executives.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2014, Landry went on to write a detailed memo outlining the idea for Prime Now, and the service launched 111 days later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/greg-satell/the-secret-behind-amazons-uncanny-ability-to-out-innovate-just-about-every-other-company-on-planet.html|title=How Amazon Innovates|last=Satell|first=Greg|date=2018-09-23|website=Inc.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] named Landry to its \"Next List 2016,\" as one of \"25 Geniuses Who Are Creating the Future of Business.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Staff|first=WIRED|url=https://www.wired.com/2016/04/wired-nextlist-2016/|title=25 Geniuses Who Are Creating the Future of Business|date=2016-04-26|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-14|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Landry, Stepheni